# Private Matters 🔐

Why make data `private`?

Imagine a `BankAccount` class.
```cpp
class BankAccount {
public:
    double balance;
};
```
If `balance` is public, anyone can do: `account.balance = -99999;` 😱

By making it private, we protect the integrity of the object.

# Controlled Access 👮

We provide public methods to access private data.

```cpp
class Account {
private:
    double balance;
public:
    // Getter
    double getBalance() {
        return balance;
    }
    // Setter
    void deposit(double amount) {
        if (amount > 0) { // Validation!
            balance += amount;
        }
    }
};
```

# A Trusted Friend 🤝

Sometimes, you want an external function to access your private secrets. You can declare it as a **friend**.

```cpp
class Box {
    int width;
public:
    friend void printWidth(Box b);
    void setWidth(int w) { width = w; }
};

void printWidth(Box b) {
    // Can access private 'width' because it's a friend
    cout << "Width: " << b.width;
}
```
> ⚠️ **Note:** Friendship is not inherited. And use it sparingly!

